SSH(1)                                                                                                  General Commands Manual                                                                                                 SSH(1)

NAME
       ssh â€” OpenSSH remote login client

SYNOPSIS
       ssh  [-46AaCfGgKkMNnqsTtVvXxYy]  [-B  bind_interface]  [-b  bind_address] [-c cipher_spec] [-D [bind_address:]port] [-E log_file] [-e escape_char] [-F configfile] [-I pkcs11] [-i identity_file] [-J destination] [-L address]
           [-l login_name] [-m mac_spec] [-O ctl_cmd] [-o option] [-P tag] [-p port] [-R address] [-S ctl_path] [-W host:port] [-w local_tun[:remote_tun]] destination [command [argument ...]]
       ssh [-Q query_option]

DESCRIPTION
       ssh (SSH client) is a program for logging into a remote machine and for executing commands on a remote machine.  It is intended to provide secure encrypted communications between two untrusted hosts over  an  insecure  netâ€
       work.  X11 connections, arbitrary TCP ports and Unix-domain sockets can also be forwarded over the secure channel.

       ssh  connects  and logs into the specified destination, which may be specified as either [user@]hostname or a URI of the form ssh://[user@]hostname[:port].  The user must prove their identity to the remote machine using one
       of several methods (see below).

       If a command is specified, it will be executed on the remote host instead of a login shell.  A complete command line may be specified as command, or it may have additional arguments.  If supplied, the arguments will be  apâ€
       pended to the command, separated by spaces, before it is sent to the server to be executed.

       The options are as follows:

